73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.25e629c8-43de-4370-b98e-c211378a30fd.description=
Service to perform HTTP POST using the Java HTTP Client.

Inputs\:
    url - The URL where to send the HTTP POST request.
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    kerberosConfFile - The  path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the  (Key Distribution Center) and  get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyusername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy server.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    file - The file to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method. This should be a path to a file/document on the disk.
    string - The raw text to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method.
    contentType - The content type that should be set in the request header, representing the MIME-type of the data in the message body.
Examples\: "text/html", "text/html; charset\=UTF-8", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded".
    characterSet - The character encoding of the text to be posted. If not specified this will be taken from the 'charset' field that can be specified in the  input. If the 'charset' field is absent, it will be set to 'ISO-8859-1' by default.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.
    headerNamesList - The list containing the header names to use for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - The list containing the header values to use for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - The list containing the names of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - The list containing the values of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separates list elements.
Default value\: ','

Results\: 
    returnCode - This is the primary output. A code used to determine the operation response, specifying whether the operation is successful or not.
    resultText - The raw result of the operation.
    document - The complete document returned by the Http Client Post Raw operation.
    URL - The URL used for the HTTP request.
    pageLoadTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken for the page to load.
    responseTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken before the server responded.
    errorMessage - An informational message that can help determine the cause of error, if an error occurred.
    httpResult - The descrition of the HTTP response returned by the web server for the request sent by this operation. This result contains the HTTP response status (for example, SUCCESS, PAGE_NOT_FOUND, UNAUTHORIZED, FORBIDDEN and so on) or GENERAL_ERROR if the HTTP request could not be executed.
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by .
    status - The HTTP response code.
Example\: HTTP/1.1 200 OK
    exception - If an error occurred, the stack trace of the thrown error.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    PAGE_NOT_FOUND - The URL specified to POST from was not found.
    INFORMATIONAL - The POST was not fully processed, the server responded with an informational response.
    REDIRECTION - The specified URL has moved.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../.cer -alias  -keystore %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
2. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
      -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
      -storepass ab987c -validity 180
It creates a certificate chain in a new keystore containing only one certificate.
3. If the value assigned to the  input is 'false' and  is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
4. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled 'Advanced Features'. Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\=,CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the 'Properties' window and press the 'Attribute Editor' tab. Observe the values of the 'servicePrincipalName' attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, HTTP/\:port.
5. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, use the  and  inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the URL. For example, http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2. If you specify the same query parameter both through the  and the  inputs, the used value is the one from the , not the one included in the .
6. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.
7. This operation uses chunked transfer encoding, which may cause failures when using HTTP servers and proxies that do not support HTTP/1.1 protocol.
73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.564a7963-af29-47be-b8dc-057569204db5.description=Generic flow to send an e-mail 73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.5797aa8e-763d-487e-a5d7-d9ebd7eab1c4.description=
Service to perform an HTTP GET via the Java HTTP Client

Inputs\:
url - the url to attempt to retrieve.
username - the username to authenticate to url with.
password - the password for username.
timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated, or 0 for no timeout.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. valid options are\: true/false
followRedirects - specifies whether or not the get command should automatically follow redirects.
trustAllRoots - enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it. valid options are\: true/false
proxy - a proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - a port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - a username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - a password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - perform URL encoding.
userAgent - if the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here
characterSet - the characterSet for HTTP Get request and response. Default is UTF-8.

Responses\:
success - URL retrieved successfully.
failure - The url could not be retrieved.
73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.61f7fb2a-b8ea-4375-9582-3be562a7bf86.description=
If the input dateFormat is not specified, it converts a date in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale, to a date either in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's or in the format specified in the input outFormat. 

If the input dateFormat is specified, it converts a date in the format in dateFormat to a date either in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's or in the format specified in the input outFormat.

You can use flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format.  

For exmaple, if OO Central Server's locale is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a". 


Specify the date format with the following patterns\:

Letter 	Date or Time Component 	Presentation 	Examples
G 	Era designator 	Text 	                     AD
y 	Year 	                     Year 	                     1996; 96
M 	Month in year 	Month 	                     July; Jul; 07
w 	Week in year 	Number 	                     27
W 	Week in month 	Number 	                     2
D 	Day in year 	                     Number 	                     189
d 	Day in month 	Number 	                     10
F 	Day of week in month 	Number 	                     2
E 	Day in week   	Text 	                     Tuesday; Tue
a 	Am/pm marker 	Text 	                     PM
H 	Hour in day (0-23) 	Number 	                     0
k 	Hour in day (1-24) 	Number 	                     24
K 	Hour in am/pm (0-11) 	Number 	                     0
h 	Hour in am/pm (1-12) 	Number 	                     12
m 	Minute in hour 	Number 	                     30
s 	Second in minute 	Number 	                     55
S 	Millisecond 	                     Number 	                     978
z 	Time zone 	                     General time zone 	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z 	Time zone 	                     RFC 822 time zone 	-0800

So, for example\: the date "2006-07-10 15\:16\:14.766 PDT" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd HH\:mm\:ss.SSS z".

You can also use single quotes (') to avoid text interpretation. The quoted text will simply be copied into the output string during formatting (if present in the outFormat) or matched against the input string during parsing (if present in the dateFormat). For example, the date value "2006-07-10T15\:16\:14.766Z" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSS'Z'". 


Inputs\:
date - The date to parse. If the input dateFormat is empty, the date must be in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale. If the input dateFormat is not empty, the date must be in the format specified in the input dateFormat.
dateFormat - The format of the input date. 
dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. For example,  en or ja.  It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. For example, US or JP.  It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty. 
outFormat - The format of the output date/time. If it is empty, the output date/time will be in the format of date/time of OO Cental Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale.
outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. For example,  en or ja. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. For example, US or JP. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.

Responses\:
success - The date was converted.
failure - The date could not be converted.

Result\:
The date in the new format.
The date in the new format.
73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.b825a8c8-4d72-4993-bf32-9685d2f8fc3c.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
Current date and time.

Responses\:
success - Date/time retrieved successfully.
failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.
73c43058-0b00-4371-9d55-694fcb537824.eae287be-f876-40e8-86b6-f8c3ce2505a9.description=
Runs a SQL query against an Oracle database, using the information in the tnsnames.ora file.  
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation. Subsequent calls with the same information return the other rows.

Inputs\:
    TNSPath -The path to the folder of the TNS file tnsnames.ora. This path must be accessible by the OO RAS service. For example, if the RAS and the Oracle server are installed on the same Windows system, the TNSPath might look like “C\:\app\Administrator\product\11.1.0\db_1\network\admin”. If the RAS and the Oracle server are on different Windows systems, you can copy the tnsnames.ora file  to the RAS system. The TNSPath might look like “C\:\Program Files\Hewlett-Packard\Operations Orchestration\RAS\Java\Default\webapp\conf” or “C\:\Temp” depending on where you place the .ora file. 
    TNSEntry - The entry name in the tnsnames.ora file that contains the connection information. For example, the value for the TNSEntry input is “TestEntry” if the content in the tnsnames.ora file looks like the following\: 

TestEntry \=
  (DESCRIPTION \=
   (ADDRESS \= (PROTOCOL \= TCP)(HOST \= 16.110.111.111)(PORT \= 1521))
   (CONNECT_DATA \=
     (SERVER \= DEDICATED)
     (SERVICE_NAME \= orcl)
   )
 )

    Username - The username to connect to the Oracle database. 
    Password - The password for the Username.
    Command - The command to execute. 
    Delimiter – The delimiter to use between the columns in the returnResult result.
    Key – The key to use to keep multiple query results distinct.
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution.
Default values\: 0 

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returned the data returned for each row separated by the value you specified in the Delimiter input (for example, “key16|lst|16”).
    columnNames - The names of the columns returned, separated by the value you specified in the Delimiter input (for example, “MYKEY|NAME|ID”).
    rowsLeft - The number of rows remaining that match the query. 

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - There was an error executing the command.

Notes\:
1. This operation only supports Oracle. 
2. This operation can only execute the "SELECT" statement. For statements that modify the database, use the TNS Names SQL Command operation.
